1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:06,021
You're listening to: QuantumShield: Building a Post-Quantum Cryptography Library from Scratch.

2
00:00:06,021 --> 00:00:17,860
Deep dive into implementing hybrid post-quantum encryption using NIST FIPS 203/204/205 standards with defense-in-depth architecture.

3
00:00:17,860 --> 00:00:24,302
Learn about ML-KEM, ML-DSA, SLH-DSA, and cascading encryption.

4
00:00:24,302 --> 00:00:25,348
Let's get started.

5
00:00:25,348 --> 00:00:29,387
Now, let's talk about Introduction: The Quantum Threat is Real.

6
00:00:29,387 --> 00:00:44,146
In 2024, NIST finalized three post-quantum cryptographic standards: FIPS 203 (ML-KEM), FIPS 204 (ML-DSA), and FIPS 205 (SLH-DSA).

7
00:00:44,146 --> 00:00:56,033
This wasn't academic exercise—it was an urgent response to a concrete threat: quantum computers capable of breaking RSA and elliptic curve cryptography are expected within the next decade.

8
00:00:56,033 --> 00:01:00,348
The "harvest now, decrypt later" attack is already happening.

9
00:01:00,348 --> 00:01:07,331
Nation-state actors collect encrypted data today, storing it until quantum computers can break current encryption.

10
00:01:07,331 --> 00:01:13,317
If your data needs to remain confidential for 10+ years, you need post-quantum cryptography today.

11
00:01:13,317 --> 00:01:23,149
This is why I built QuantumShield—an open-source post-quantum cryptography library implementing defense-in-depth architecture with NIST-approved algorithms.

12
00:01:23,149 --> 00:01:25,841
Moving on to The NIST Post-Quantum Standards.

13
00:01:25,841 --> 00:01:32,644
FIPS 203: ML-KEM (Module-Lattice Key Encapsulation Mechanism).

14
00:01:32,644 --> 00:01:42,776
ML-KEM (formerly CRYSTALS-Kyber) is a key encapsulation mechanism based on the hardness of the Module Learning With Errors (MLWE) problem.

15
00:01:42,776 --> 00:01:44,086
Key properties:

16
00:01:44,086 --> 00:01:57,956
Security levels: ML-KEM-512 (128-bit), ML-KEM-768 (192-bit), ML-KEM-1024 (256-bit).

17
00:01:57,956 --> 00:02:03,557
Performance: Fast key generation, encapsulation, and decapsulation.

18
00:02:03,557 --> 00:02:08,461
Key sizes: Public keys ~1KB, ciphertexts ~1KB.

19
00:02:08,461 --> 00:02:15,384
QuantumShield uses ML-KEM-768 for a balance of security and performance.

20
00:02:15,384 --> 00:02:21,995
FIPS 204: ML-DSA (Module-Lattice Digital Signature Algorithm).

21
00:02:21,995 --> 00:02:28,665
ML-DSA (formerly CRYSTALS-Dilithium) provides digital signatures based on lattice problems:

22
00:02:28,665 --> 00:02:43,040
Security levels: ML-DSA-44 (128-bit), ML-DSA-65 (192-bit), ML-DSA-87 (256-bit).

23
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:48,786
Signature size: ~2.4KB for ML-DSA-65.

24
00:02:48,786 --> 00:02:52,740
Fast verification: Important for high-throughput systems.

25
00:02:52,740 --> 00:03:00,024
FIPS 205: SLH-DSA (Stateless Hash-Based Digital Signature Algorithm).

26
00:03:00,024 --> 00:03:06,875
SLH-DSA (formerly SPHINCS+) offers an alternative based purely on hash functions:

27
00:03:06,875 --> 00:03:11,875
Conservative choice: Security relies only on hash function properties.

28
00:03:11,875 --> 00:03:17,620
Larger signatures: ~8KB for SHAKE-128f variant.

29
00:03:17,620 --> 00:03:22,932
Cryptographic diversity: Different mathematical foundation than lattice-based schemes.

30
00:03:22,932 --> 00:03:25,480
Next up: QuantumShield Architecture.

31
00:03:25,480 --> 00:03:31,622
QuantumShield doesn't just implement these algorithms—it layers them for defense-in-depth.

32
00:03:31,622 --> 00:03:35,817
Even if one algorithm is compromised, your data remains secure.

33
00:03:35,817 --> 00:03:39,915
Layer 1: Hybrid Key Encapsulation (QShieldKEM).

34
00:03:39,915 --> 00:03:40,889
Why hybrid?

35
00:03:40,889 --> 00:03:45,600
X25519 is battle-tested and widely deployed.

36
00:03:45,600 --> 00:03:50,240
ML-KEM-768 provides quantum resistance.

37
00:03:50,240 --> 00:03:51,598
By combining both:

38
00:03:51,598 --> 00:03:58,125
If X25519 is broken by quantum computers, ML-KEM protects you.

39
00:03:58,125 --> 00:04:05,012
If ML-KEM has an undiscovered vulnerability, X25519 protects you.

40
00:04:05,012 --> 00:04:09,098
An attacker must break both to compromise the key exchange.

41
00:04:09,098 --> 00:04:12,536
Layer 2: Dual Signatures (QShieldSign).

42
00:04:12,536 --> 00:04:14,002
Why dual signatures?

43
00:04:14,002 --> 00:04:19,951
ML-DSA and SLH-DSA use fundamentally different mathematics:

44
00:04:19,951 --> 00:04:23,834
ML-DSA: Based on lattice problems (MLWE).

45
00:04:23,834 --> 00:04:27,812
SLH-DSA: Based purely on hash functions.

46
00:04:27,812 --> 00:04:33,882
If a breakthrough breaks lattice cryptography, hash-based signatures remain secure (and vice versa).

47
00:04:33,882 --> 00:04:37,572
Layer 3: Cascading Encryption (QuantumShield).

48
00:04:37,572 --> 00:04:39,290
Why cascading encryption?

49
00:04:39,290 --> 00:04:46,682
AES-256-GCM: NIST-approved, hardware-accelerated, widely analyzed.

50
00:04:46,682 --> 00:04:53,954
ChaCha20-Poly1305: IETF standard, excellent software performance, different design.

51
00:04:53,954 --> 00:04:57,728
An attacker must break both ciphers to decrypt your data.

52
00:04:57,728 --> 00:04:59,254
This protects against:

53
00:04:59,254 --> 00:05:02,319
Cryptanalytic breakthroughs in either cipher.

54
00:05:02,319 --> 00:05:05,600
Implementation vulnerabilities in either library.

55
00:05:05,600 --> 00:05:09,050
Side-channel attacks that might affect one but not both.

56
00:05:09,050 --> 00:05:11,177
Let's explore Security Properties.

57
00:05:11,177 --> 00:05:12,932
Constant-Time Operations.

58
00:05:12,932 --> 00:05:20,252
All cryptographic operations in QuantumShield are implemented in constant time to prevent timing side-channel attacks:

59
00:05:20,252 --> 00:05:22,776
Automatic Memory Zeroization.

60
00:05:22,776 --> 00:05:26,862
Secrets are automatically scrubbed from memory when no longer needed:

61
00:05:26,862 --> 00:05:29,350
Domain-Separated Key Derivation.

62
00:05:29,354 --> 00:05:35,397
Every derived key uses a unique domain separator to prevent key confusion attacks:

63
00:05:35,397 --> 00:05:37,152
Perfect Forward Secrecy.

64
00:05:37,152 --> 00:05:41,070
QuantumShield generates ephemeral keys for each session.

65
00:05:41,070 --> 00:05:46,142
If long-term keys are compromised, past communications remain secure:

66
00:05:46,142 --> 00:05:48,522
Now let's look at Performance Considerations.

67
00:05:48,522 --> 00:05:54,159
Post-quantum algorithms have larger keys and signatures than classical cryptography.

68
00:05:54,159 --> 00:05:56,707
Here's how QuantumShield's sizes compare:

69
00:05:56,707 --> 00:06:00,133
Component, Classical, QuantumShield, Overhead.

70
00:06:00,133 --> 00:06:08,751
Public Key, ~32 bytes (X25519), ~1.2 KB, ~37x.

71
00:06:08,751 --> 00:06:14,484
Secret Key, ~32 bytes, ~2.5 KB, ~78x.

72
00:06:14,484 --> 00:06:19,520
Ciphertext, ~32 bytes, ~1.1 KB, ~34x.

73
00:06:19,520 --> 00:06:27,200
Signature, ~64 bytes (Ed25519), ~10.5 KB, ~164x.

74
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:28,787
Performance tradeoffs:

75
00:06:28,787 --> 00:06:32,116
Key generation: ~10x slower than classical.

76
00:06:32,116 --> 00:06:37,104
Encryption/Decryption: ~2x slower due to cascading.

77
00:06:37,104 --> 00:06:39,953
Signature creation: ~5x slower.

78
00:06:39,953 --> 00:06:42,993
Signature verification: ~3x slower.

79
00:06:42,993 --> 00:06:46,683
For most applications, these overheads are acceptable.

80
00:06:46,683 --> 00:06:51,455
Network latency typically dominates over cryptographic operations.

81
00:06:51,455 --> 00:06:53,642
Now, let's talk about Use Cases.

82
00:06:53,642 --> 00:06:55,097
Healthcare (HIPAA).

83
00:06:55,097 --> 00:07:00,349
Protected Health Information (PHI) must remain confidential for decades.

84
00:07:00,349 --> 00:07:06,371
A 30-year-old patient's records from 2026 might still be relevant in 2076.

85
00:07:06,371 --> 00:07:13,066
QuantumShield ensures that data encrypted today cannot be decrypted by quantum computers in the future.

86
00:07:13,066 --> 00:07:14,604
Financial Services.

87
00:07:14,604 --> 00:07:20,758
Transaction records, account data, and trading algorithms require long-term confidentiality.

88
00:07:20,758 --> 00:07:28,162
Regulatory requirements often mandate data retention for 7+ years—well within the quantum threat window.

89
00:07:28,162 --> 00:07:29,808
Government & Defense.

90
00:07:29,808 --> 00:07:35,602
Classified information often remains sensitive for 25-75 years.

91
00:07:35,602 --> 00:07:42,873
The "harvest now, decrypt later" threat is particularly acute for national security applications.

92
00:07:42,873 --> 00:07:44,364
Long-term Archives.

93
00:07:44,364 --> 00:07:54,532
Legal documents, intellectual property, research data, and personal records that must remain confidential for 50+ years need quantum-safe encryption from day one.

94
00:07:54,532 --> 00:07:58,703
Moving on to Honest Assessment: What QuantumShield Is (and Isn't).

95
00:07:58,703 --> 00:08:02,104
Transparency is essential in cryptography.

96
00:08:02,104 --> 00:08:05,517
Let me be upfront about QuantumShield's current state:

97
00:08:05,517 --> 00:08:06,611
What It Does Well.

98
00:08:06,611 --> 00:08:18,306
Real NIST algorithms: The hybrid KEM uses ML-KEM-768 from the fips203 crate—a pure Rust implementation of FIPS 203.

99
00:08:18,306 --> 00:08:22,909
This isn't a toy implementation; it's the actual standardized algorithm..

100
00:08:22,909 --> 00:08:38,426
Battle-tested primitives: The underlying cryptographic primitives (AES-GCM, ChaCha20-Poly1305, X25519, Argon2id) come from well-audited Rust crates maintained by the RustCrypto team..

101
00:08:38,426 --> 00:08:47,561
Defense-in-depth architecture: The hybrid approach (combining classical + post-quantum) follows NIST's own recommendations for migration strategies..

102
00:08:47,561 --> 00:08:57,380
Memory safety: Rust's ownership model and automatic zeroization provide real security benefits that are hard to achieve in C/C++..

103
00:08:57,380 --> 00:08:58,991
Important Caveats.

104
00:08:58,991 --> 00:09:02,416
Not professionally audited: This is a personal project.

105
00:09:02,416 --> 00:09:10,049
While the underlying algorithm implementations are from reputable sources, the integration hasn't been reviewed by professional cryptographers..

106
00:09:10,049 --> 00:09:22,645
Large signature sizes: The dual signature system (ML-DSA-65 + SLH-DSA-SHAKE-128f) produces ~20KB signatures.

107
00:09:22,645 --> 00:09:25,626
This is a tradeoff for defense-in-depth security..

108
00:09:25,626 --> 00:09:39,520
Not production-ready: For systems protecting sensitive data in production, use established libraries like liboqs from Open Quantum Safe, or wait for major libraries like OpenSSL/BoringSSL to integrate PQC..

109
00:09:39,520 --> 00:09:49,953
Algorithm composition is new: While individual algorithms are NIST-approved, combining them in novel ways creates new attack surfaces that haven't been formally analyzed..

110
00:09:49,953 --> 00:09:55,818
Performance vs. security tradeoffs: The cascading encryption approach adds overhead.

111
00:09:55,818 --> 00:10:00,554
For most applications, a single well-implemented cipher is sufficient..

112
00:10:00,554 --> 00:10:02,272
When to Use QuantumShield.

113
00:10:02,272 --> 00:10:06,779
Learning: Excellent for understanding how PQC works in practice.

114
00:10:06,779 --> 00:10:11,779
Prototyping: Testing PQC integration in non-critical systems.

115
00:10:11,779 --> 00:10:15,614
Research: Exploring hybrid cryptography approaches.

116
00:10:15,614 --> 00:10:19,616
Personal projects: Where you understand and accept the risks.

117
00:10:19,616 --> 00:10:21,587
When NOT to Use QuantumShield.

118
00:10:21,602 --> 00:10:24,821
Production systems handling sensitive user data.

119
00:10:24,821 --> 00:10:29,652
Healthcare/financial applications with regulatory requirements.

120
00:10:29,652 --> 00:10:33,667
Any system where cryptographic failure has serious consequences.

121
00:10:33,667 --> 00:10:43,030
The goal of this project is to demonstrate that post-quantum cryptography is accessible and practical—not to replace battle-hardened production libraries.

122
00:10:43,030 --> 00:10:48,330
Consider it a learning tool and a proof-of-concept, not a drop-in security solution.

123
00:10:48,330 --> 00:10:49,989
Next up: Getting Started.

124
