138
00:11:40,253 --> 00:11:41,984
Now, let's talk about Conclusion.

139
00:11:41,984 --> 00:11:46,972
The quantum computing threat isn't science fiction—it's an engineering timeline.

140
00:11:46,972 --> 00:11:54,532
NIST has finalized the standards (FIPS 203/204/205).

141
00:11:54,532 --> 00:11:56,131
The algorithms are ready.

142
00:11:56,131 --> 00:12:00,049
Organizations should begin planning their migration strategies now.

143
00:12:00,049 --> 00:12:09,616
QuantumShield demonstrates one approach: defense-in-depth architecture combining hybrid key exchange, cascading encryption, and (soon) dual signatures.

144
00:12:09,616 --> 00:12:15,157
It's built to show that post-quantum cryptography is accessible to Rust developers today.

145
00:12:15,157 --> 00:12:20,854
My honest take: Building this taught me that PQC is more approachable than I expected.

146
00:12:20,854 --> 00:12:26,359
The algorithms work, the performance is acceptable, and the tooling is maturing.

147
00:12:26,359 --> 00:12:38,703
But cryptography is hard, and getting it right in production requires more than just calling the right APIs—it requires professional review, formal verification, and continuous security monitoring.

148
00:12:38,703 --> 00:12:46,912
If you're building systems today that need long-term confidentiality (10+ years), start evaluating PQC options now.

149
00:12:46,912 --> 00:12:54,520
But use established, audited implementations from organizations like Open Quantum Safe, not personal projects like this one.

150
00:12:54,520 --> 00:13:04,412
QuantumShield's value is in education and experimentation—demonstrating that the post-quantum future is buildable today, one hybrid key exchange at a time.

151
00:13:04,412 --> 00:13:08,198
QuantumShield is open source under the MIT license.

152
00:13:08,198 --> 00:13:15,205
View on GitHub or try the live demo to see ML-KEM-768 running in your browser.

153
00:13:15,205 --> 00:13:16,900
And that's the end of this article.

154
00:13:16,900 --> 00:13:18,006
Thanks for listening.

